Steven Swiniarski wrote:
>
>PROTO: The General Fund
>
>Preface: This was inspired by Oerjan's comment that Indulgences were
>a closed system.  The fact is, the one reason we have inflation is
>because we mint money whenever we need it.  

I disagree with that analysis. The reason we have inflation is that
inputs (Currency leaving the Bank and going into circulation) exceed
outputs (Currency leaving circulation and returning to the Bank).
Now admittedly, a taxation Proposal such as you outline here is one
way of forcing outputs to at least equal inputs - but the fact 
that it's forced is the main reason to oppose it. The general thrust
of all the recent efforts to get a balanced and interesting economy
where commodities are scarce and therefore valuable has been to
achieve this without using brute force, by designing a system in
which commodities are more difficult to obtain than they are to spend. 
A taxation proposal which doesn't address the excess of inputs
into the economy simply takes blindly with one hand what it gives 
blindly with the other. It makes much more sense simply not to
give so much in the first place and so obviate the need for
taking.



